help and even making it fun and
joyful is

37:49.367 --> 37:51.703 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a good start.

37:51.736 --> 37:59.811 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour" and
Kaiser Health News,
I'm Sarah Varney in Memphis.

37:59.844 --> 38:13.024 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now a
startling expose about
slave labor in the world of
seafood.

38:13.057 --> 38:17.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This week, we're looking at some
of the Pulitzer
Prize winners. And the
Associated Press' 18-month-long

38:17.795 --> 38:23.501 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
investigation won the prize for
public service.
It tracked the widespread use of
slave labor

38:23.535 --> 38:29.374 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in Southeast Asia and how it's
part in a supply
chain bringing seafood to
American restaurants

38:29.407 --> 38:31.209 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and supermarkets.

38:31.242 --> 38:35.980 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Fishermen were beaten and caged,
and reporters
even hid in the back of trucks
for days to

38:36.014 --> 38:40.552 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
pursue the story. Since then,
more than 2,000
slaves have been freed.

38:40.585 --> 38:43.855 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Martha Mendoza was part of that
reporting
team, and joins me now.

38:43.888 --> 38:48.860 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Martha, what was the catalyst
for the investigation
in the first place?
Unfortunately, we have

38:48.893 --> 38:53.831 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
heard of slave-like conditions
in different
parts of the world before. What
made you want

38:53.865 --> 38:55.700 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to follow this?

38:55.733 --> 38:59.370 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARTHA MENDOZA, Associated
Press: Well, Slavery
at sea wasn't a secret, but the
stories that

38:59.404 --> 39:02.073 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
were being told came from
rescued slaves.

39:02.106 --> 39:07.378 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, therefore, there was no
traction because
the response was, these guys are
safe. There

39:07.412 --> 39:11.549 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is not really a problem anymore.
So, we set
out to do what some people
warned us was going

39:11.583 --> 39:16.754 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to be impossible. We wanted to
find captive
slaves, and then we wanted to
track their

39:16.788 --> 39:21.459 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
catch with detailed accuracy all
the way back
to the dinner table to get
people who were

39:21.492 --> 39:23.995 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
at the other end of this supply
chain engaged.

39:24.028 --> 39:28.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, how do you
find the
captive slaves in the first
place?

39:28.366 --> 39:34.405 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARTHA MENDOZA: My colleagues
spoke at length
and for many months with people
who had escaped,

39:34.439 --> 39:37.809 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
as well as human rights
activists who worked
with people who had escaped.

39:37.842 --> 39:43.982 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they had some miss, going to
places where
this wasn't happening or false
leads. But

39:44.015 --> 39:48.286 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
when they heard about this
island in Indonesia
called Benjina, they had a
pretty good idea

39:48.319 --> 39:53.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there might be labor abuse going
on there.
And it was a plane trip to a
boat ride to

39:53.891 --> 39:57.829 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a second boat ride to an island
that can only
be reached at certain times of
the year.

39:57.862 --> 40:02.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's where my colleagues
did, indeed,
find a slave island.

40:02.033 --> 40:04.936 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, when they
get to this
island, obviously, it's not the
red carpet.

40:04.969 --> 40:08.873 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I mean, are you hiding
throughout this process
when you're trying to document
what is on

40:08.906 --> 40:11.309 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the island, who lives here, what
the conditions
are?

40:11.342 --> 40:15.446 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARTHA MENDOZA: Well, actually,
the AP reporters,
the AP team split up.

40:15.480 --> 40:20.618 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So, some were ostensibly
interested in the
fishing operations, and others
were at the

40:20.652 --> 40:24.656 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
same time kind of checking out
other parts
of what was happening on the
island. When

40:24.689 --> 40:29.494 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Robin McDowell, who was there,
realized that
a number of the men were from
Burma, she asked

40:29.527 --> 40:35.099 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Esther Htusan to fly and boat,
make the trip
there to Burma.

40:35.133 --> 40:39.003 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when Esther arrived, that's
when the story
really broke open for her,
because these men

40:39.037 --> 40:43.808 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
wanted to tell her their story.
They were
shoving pieces of papers in
their hands with

40:43.841 --> 40:47.378 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
their parents' names and phone
numbers and
their villages begging them to
tell their

40:47.412 --> 40:49.847 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
families back home that they
were alive.

40:49.881 --> 40:54.585 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when they asked to see more
of these men,
they actually were taken to a
graveyard with

40:54.619 --> 40:58.890 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
more than 70 bodies and false
names on the
signs above them.

40:58.923 --> 41:03.328 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So what's the
trail? What's
the paper trail between how that
seafood that

41:03.361 --> 41:07.732 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
these slaves are fishing
actually gets to
a grocery store in the United
States?

41:07.765 --> 41:12.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARTHA MENDOZA: Well, we videoed
and documented
the seafood being loaded on to
one refrigerated

41:12.970 --> 41:14.772 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
cargo ship.

41:14.806 --> 41:20.812 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That boat had a satellite
tracker in it, and
that tracker was pinging to a
locator, and

41:20.845 --> 41:25.450 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we watched the boat via the
Internet. And
for two weeks, we tracked it
into port. When

41:25.483 --> 41:32.056 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it arrived in port, AP met it
and watched
the seafood being unloaded into
pickup trucks,

41:32.090 --> 41:34.292 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and followed those trucks to
factories.

41:34.325 --> 41:39.397 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We were able to search and find
the companies
in Thailand that were then
shipping to the

41:39.430 --> 41:44.702 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
United States, and go to these
American seafood
distributors to figure out where
their fish

41:44.736 --> 41:46.471 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
ends up.

41:46.504 --> 41:48.473 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A lot of time, when you're in a
supermarket,
you're going to see a piece of
fish under

41:48.506 --> 41:53.144 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
some clear plastic wrap with a
label on it.
It's not even going to say which
distributor

41:53.177 --> 41:58.049 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it came from. So, there was a
lot of steps
in between. But, eventually, we
were able

41:58.082 --> 42:05.289 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
to track it to Wal-Mart,
Safeway, Sysco, Albertsons,
and products like Fancy Feasts
and Iams as

42:05.323 --> 42:07.091 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
well.

42:07.125 --> 42:10.128 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right, so
since story,
more than 2000 men have been
freed. And you

42:10.161 --> 42:13.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
were able to document some of
those stories
of them reuniting with their
families.

42:13.398 --> 42:15.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARTHA MENDOZA: Yes.

42:15.166 --> 42:19.404 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So about a week after we
finished our story,
authorities went to the island
of Benjina

42:19.437 --> 42:24.509 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and began interviewing men. They
talked to
a couple who described their
horrific, desperate

42:24.542 --> 42:29.180 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
situation and also told the
authorities that
they would be beaten and hurt
for telling

42:29.213 --> 42:33.184 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
their story. And they were told,
no, we're
going to rescue you.

42:33.217 --> 42:36.654 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Word got out on the island, and
pretty soon
they just went ahead and made
the announcement,

42:36.687 --> 42:40.458 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
anyone who wants to come with us
can come.
And hundreds of people began
pouring down

42:40.491 --> 42:44.529 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to the docks, jumping out of
boat windows,
running out of the jungle.

42:44.562 --> 42:50.768 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And on that day alone, 400 --
close to 400
men were rescued. And, yes, it
grew to 2,000.

42:50.802 --> 42:57.275 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One man we followed home, Myint
Naing, had
been gone for 22 years. His
sister saw him

42:57.308 --> 43:01.212 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
walking into the village, and
screamed and
cried and held him. And then,
when his mother

43:01.245 --> 43:07.685 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
saw him, she was actually
overwhelmed and
had to -- she lost her breath
for a while.

43:07.718 --> 43:10.455 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It was a very sweet and moving
moment.

43:10.488 --> 43:13.691 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: What's the
Thai government
said that they would do or what
have they

43:13.724 --> 43:15.426 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
done since this has been
published?

43:15.460 --> 43:20.698 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MARTHA MENDOZA: The Thai
government, prior
to us publishing and as we
published story

43:20.731 --> 43:28.039 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
after story, kept making
commitments to do
better. They have made it so
that, if you

43:28.072 --> 43:31.976 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
are a victim of human
trafficking, they say
are you no longer treated as an
illegal immigrant

43:32.009 --> 43:34.679 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and simply deported as a
criminal.

43:34.712 --> 43:43.054 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
They have vowed to make
prosecutions more
of a priority, and one of the
pieces of this

43:43.087 --> 43:49.160 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
we did involved shrimp
processing. And the
shrimp sector there in Thailand
has -- says

43:49.193 --> 43:52.897 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they're moving all shrimp
processing in house.
So they're not going to
outsource any shrimp

43:52.930 --> 43:55.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
processing in sheds, where there
is much less
oversight.

43:55.366 --> 43:58.636 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
Martha Mendoza
of the Associated Press, thanks
so much.

43:58.669 --> 44:05.877 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARTHA MENDOZA: Thank you, Hari.

44:05.910 --> 44:16.988 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now a new take on
coping with
the anxieties of middle age.
It's the newest

44:17.021 --> 44:19.357 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
addition to the "NewsHour"
Bookshelf.

44:19.390 --> 44:21.225 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Jeffrey Brown has that.

44:21.259 --> 44:26.531 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Personal
disappointment, a
stagnating career, feelings of
physical decline,

44:26.564 --> 44:31.235 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the classic descriptions of a
midlife crisis.
But do we have that all wrong?

44:31.269 --> 44:36.908 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
"Life Reimagined: The Science,
Art, and Opportunity
of Midlife" takes the challenge
of answering

44:36.941 --> 44:38.709 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
that.

44:38.743 --> 44:42.413 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Author Barbara Bradley Hagerty
spent nearly
20 years with NPR covering law
and religion

44:42.446 --> 44:45.316 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
before, well, she changed her
own midlife.

44:45.349 --> 44:47.251 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And welcome to you.

44:47.285 --> 44:48.085 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY, Author,
"Life Reimagined:
The Science, Art, and
Opportunity of Midlife":

44:48.119 --> 44:49.887 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Thank you. It's great to be
here.

44:49.921 --> 44:51.389 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, the first
main finding
seems to be that the so-called
midlife crisis

44:51.422 --> 44:53.691 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is really a kind of made-up
construct.

44:53.724 --> 44:55.526 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY: It is.

44:55.560 --> 44:58.229 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We had this kind of cultural
transformation,
when everyone thought we had to
have a midlife

44:58.262 --> 45:02.466 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
crisis. Everyone had to buy a
sports car or
dump their spouse or something
like that.

45:02.500 --> 45:07.471 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then what happened is, in
the mid-1990s,
U.S. psychologists started to
say, is there

45:07.505 --> 45:11.475 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
really such a thing as a midlife
crisis? Is
it common? How common is it?

45:11.509 --> 45:15.246 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when they began to look at
this, what
they found is that only about 10
percent of

45:15.279 --> 45:20.551 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
people have a classic midlife
crisis, which
is this kind of existential
angst about dying

45:20.585 --> 45:22.920 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
before you can achieve your
dreams, only about
10 point.

45:22.954 --> 45:26.390 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Short of that,
though, everyone
does go through stages, right?
Everyone has

45:26.424 --> 45:27.224 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
turning points.

45:27.258 --> 45:28.426 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY: You do.

45:28.459 --> 45:29.827 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You yourself had
-- it got
you writing.

45:29.860 --> 45:31.596 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY: I also
had one. That's
right. That's right.

45:31.629 --> 45:36.734 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, while midlife crisis is
not all that
common, midlife ennui, that kind
of malaise

45:36.767 --> 45:41.739 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
that people have, that's
actually very, very
common. People generally are
happy in their

45:41.772 --> 45:46.744 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
20s and 30s, and then they kind
of get discontented
in their 40s and 50s. And then
they swoop

45:46.777 --> 45:50.348 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
back up and they're very happy
in their late
kind of 50s, 60s, 70s.

45:50.381 --> 45:55.086 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so there's this nadir at
midlife, generally
around 45 in America.

45:55.119 --> 46:00.124 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You approach this
as the reporter
you are. You talked to lots of
people. Right?

46:00.157 --> 46:06.297 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What struck you most about the
kinds of crises,
or let's call it a slump, that
you would find

46:06.330 --> 46:08.132 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
from people? What kind of
things?

46:08.165 --> 46:11.502 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY: This
was done shortly
after the 2008 recession. That
was the most

46:11.535 --> 46:14.972 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
common trigger to this midlife
slump that
people had.

46:15.006 --> 46:20.244 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, basically, if you're 50 and
you lose
your job, it is really hard to
find another

46:20.277 --> 46:25.116 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
one. So, what I kind of found
was, 55 is the
new 65. That's what people were
finding. It

46:25.149 --> 46:26.884 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
was very difficult.

46:26.917 --> 46:32.289 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But almost without exception,
the people I
talked to who were in that slump
eventually

46:32.323 --> 46:36.427 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
did find another job, and they
were much happier.
And the point here that was
really interesting

46:36.460 --> 46:39.864 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is, people generally return to
their happiness
set point.

46:39.897 --> 46:41.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Happiness set --
what does
that mean?

46:41.799 --> 46:44.568 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY: It just
means that
people have a certain set point.

46:44.602 --> 46:49.607 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm a little bit happier than my
husband.
If something happens to me, I
will return

46:49.640 --> 46:53.811 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to my happiness set point, kind
of my average
happiness level. His might be
different from

46:53.844 --> 46:57.581 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
mine. Everyone has a little bit
of a different
one, but you return to your
norm.

46:57.615 --> 47:01.285 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Tell me about key
findings
that places like the wonderfully
named Happiness

47:01.318 --> 47:04.255 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Research Center in Copenhagen
are coming to.

47:04.288 --> 47:06.924 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY: Well,
what they did
is, they looked at job
satisfaction.

47:06.957 --> 47:12.029 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what they found is that the
key thing
to job satisfaction, the most
important thing

47:12.063 --> 47:17.034 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is having a purpose, feeling
like your job
has a purpose. And so it could
be either that

47:17.068 --> 47:21.038 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you feel your job personally has
a purpose
or that you're part of an
organization with

47:21.072 --> 47:23.340 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a greater mission.

47:23.374 --> 47:26.877 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Purpose turns out to be like the
magic bullet
for happiness.

47:26.911 --> 47:28.612 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Across the board?

47:28.646 --> 47:30.481 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY: Across
the board,
not just at work, but having a
purpose in

47:30.514 --> 47:35.686 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
life tends to makes you
healthier. It means
that you stave off dementia
better than other

47:35.720 --> 47:37.588 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
people.

47:37.621 --> 47:40.891 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It means that you're much less
likely to have
a stroke or be sick. It is a
wonderful quality

47:40.925 --> 47:44.495 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to have, this idea that you have
purpose in
life, you have a reason to get
out of bed

47:44.528 --> 47:46.397 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in the morning.

47:46.430 --> 47:48.632 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You also are
looking at people
who have made changes in their
lives, right?

47:48.666 --> 47:53.504 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How do you make those changes?
How do you
decide big things, like changing
a job, for

47:53.537 --> 47:59.910 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
example? When is it time to --
if I'm not
happy at the job, what do I do
next? Because

47:59.944 --> 48:00.778 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that's not easy either.

48:00.811 --> 48:02.546 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY: Right.
Right.

48:02.580 --> 48:06.050 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, one thing that career
experts say you
shouldn't do is just kind of
leave your job

48:06.083 --> 48:10.187 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and follow your muse. You're an
accountant,
and you want to be a Hollywood
star. That

48:10.221 --> 48:11.989 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
usually doesn't work out so
well.

48:12.022 --> 48:16.293 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So what you need to do is really
think about,
what is -- what am I really good
at? What

48:16.327 --> 48:21.031 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
do I love doing? Is there a way
to pivot on
that so that even within the
company I work

48:21.065 --> 48:26.036 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for, or the organization I work,
I can do
more of that than less of things
I'm really

48:26.070 --> 48:28.005 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
bad at?

48:28.038 --> 48:31.509 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, if you're an editor
who has been
put up in management, and you
don't like management,

48:31.542 --> 48:33.711 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
go back to being an editor. So,
that's one
thing.

48:33.744 --> 48:37.748 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The other thing that people can
do is, while
they're exploring what they want
to do next,

48:37.782 --> 48:41.652 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they should dip a toe in the
water. And by
that, I mean, they should
volunteer at an

48:41.685 --> 48:45.489 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
organization that they think
they might like.
They should take classes.

48:45.523 --> 48:49.260 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I talked to one man who was an
investment
banker who went to divinity
school at night,

48:49.293 --> 48:54.331 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and now he's a minister. So
that's the other
thing. You should be careful
about it. Look

48:54.365 --> 48:56.400 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
deep inside yourself and then
take the leap.

48:56.433 --> 49:00.905 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: I have to ask you
this, because
the baby boom generation, and,
to some degree,

49:00.938 --> 49:08.112 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Gen-Xers, are famously derided
for being self-absorbed,
right, full of ourselves. Right?

49:08.145 --> 49:15.286 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Is this a discussion just for
those who can
either, A, afford it, those who
are a little

49:15.319 --> 49:17.621 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
bit more absorbed with
themselves than perhaps
we should be?

49:17.655 --> 49:19.423 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY: Right.

49:19.456 --> 49:23.427 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, I must say that midlife
crisis is a
privileged problem to have.
People who are

49:23.460 --> 49:29.900 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
working two jobs, both partners
working two
jobs, and they have kids, and
they don't have

49:29.934 --> 49:35.005 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
really a lot of time to look
deep into themselves
and wonder if they're
existentially happy.

49:35.039 --> 49:36.874 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right?

49:36.907 --> 49:41.278 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So it is really something for
the privileged,
people in the middle class or
even a little

49:41.312 --> 49:43.380 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
wealthier, who can afford to
have a midlife
crisis.

49:43.414 --> 49:47.151 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And this is, in
part, a memoir,
right?

49:47.184 --> 49:48.619 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY: It is.

49:48.652 --> 49:49.486 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, is in part...

49:49.520 --> 49:50.020 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY: It is.
It is.

49:50.054 --> 49:51.722 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

49:51.755 --> 49:52.823 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY: And the
reason I
did it that way is because I
think I wanted

49:52.857 --> 49:54.692 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
people to know that I was going
through this
too.

49:54.725 --> 49:58.195 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I looked at all the parts that I
think are
important in life. I looked at
midlife marriage,

49:58.229 --> 50:02.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
midlife brain, midlife
friendships, midlife
career, that kind of thing. When
bad things

50:02.566 --> 50:06.804 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
happen, what does resilience
research say?
So I looked at kind of all of
these parts

50:06.837 --> 50:11.308 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of my life that I thought were
really, really
important. And then I said, how
do you thrive?

50:11.342 --> 50:13.177 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How do you thrive at midlife
marriage?

50:13.210 --> 50:17.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How do you thrive? How do you
make your midlife
brain be sharper? That's how I
approached

50:17.381 --> 50:18.182 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
it.

50:18.215 --> 50:19.116 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And you're doing
OK?

50:19.149 --> 50:20.084 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY: I'm
doing great.

50:20.117 --> 50:21.952 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

50:21.986 --> 50:25.055 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right, the
book is -- good,
because you want people to buy
the book, right?

50:25.089 --> 50:28.659 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
"Life Reimagined" is the book,
"The Science,
Art, and Opportunity of
Midlife."

50:28.692 --> 50:30.961 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Barbara Bradley Hagerty, thanks
so much.

50:30.995 --> 50:39.169 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BARBARA BRADLEY HAGERTY: It's
been a pleasure.
Thank you.

50:39.203 --> 50:42.840 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Stay tuned.

50:42.873 --> 50:48.078 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Later tonight on "NOVA":
National parks are
key to protecting wildlife, but
even the largest

50:48.112 --> 50:53.517 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
preserves are often too small to
maintain
diversity and healthy
populations. Researchers

50:53.550 --> 50:56.787 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
set out to find a solution.

50:56.820 --> 51:03.994 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NARRATOR: Another major barrier
to wildlife
is the four-lane highway. With
several lanes

51:04.028 --> 51:14.972 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of traffic and speeding cars and
trucks, these
roads can be death traps.

51:15.005 --> 51:23.781 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Many animals are not as lucky as
this cub.
